Using a sharp knife, trim the sea bass fillets into a square shape, then cut into the skin side to lightly score.Rub the fillets with olive oil and season with salt and a pinch of white pepper and ground coriander.Heat a frying pan until hot and add the sea bass, skin-side down. Fry for three minutes, then turn and cook for a further 1-2 minutes, or until completely cooked through.For the fennel pesto, place the fennel into a food processor and blend to a fine pur√©e.Add the dill, pine nuts, ground almonds and parmesan and pulse to combine.Add the olive oil and blend to a porridge-like consistency. Season, to taste, with salt and freshly ground black pepper.For the tomato salsa, place the tomatoes into a bowl and add the lemon juice, sesame oil, Tabasco sauce and coriander leaves. Stir gently to combine.To serve, place a spoonful of fennel pesto into the centre of each plate. Place a sea bass fillet on top of each and spoon the salsa around. Garnish with a few pea shoots and serve.